## 📖 When to Use `./` Prefix

`./` tells the terminal "this is a file path" not a command or flag.
Only needed when a filename **starts with** a character the terminal misinterprets.

| Filename Starts With | Problem Without `./` | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| `-` hyphen | Read as a flag/option | `cat ./-` |
| `--` double hyphen | Read as a flag/option | `cat ./--filename` |
| `~` tilde | Interpreted as home directory | `cat ./~file` |
| `$` dollar | Interpreted as a variable | `cat ./$file` |
| `!` exclamation | Triggers history expansion | `cat ./!file` |
| `...` dots | No misinterpretation — `./` not needed | `cat ...filename` |

**Note:** `./` only fixes problems at the **start** of a filename.
For spaces anywhere in the name, use quotes or `\` instead.
For filenames with both hyphens AND spaces, combine both fixes.
